Overview¶

FOCUS has implemented the periodicity of coils by using IsSymmetric=2. In principle, FOCUS optimized coils should conserve periodicity and stellarator symmetry if the target plasma has the properties. However, one might terminate the optimization before reaching the minimum by many reasons. In that sense, FOCUS optimized coils might not be strictly symmetric. A recent presentation by J. Schmitt indicates that finite asymmetry in coils may cause sizable differences in Boozer harmonics. Here, I imported the feature to conserve stellarator symmetry and change the implementation of periodicity.

New implementation of periodicity¶

The plasma and coils are both periodic. In FOCUS calculations, we can only consider one period plasma, but we have to compute the magnetic field generated by all coils. If we have a case of Nfp = N, only coils in the first period $C_1$ will be treated as free variables. We have to calculate the magnetic field from it and its periodic coils on the point $P_1$. What FOCUS was doing is to

  • Map the coils to the entire toroidal region and we have and its periodic coils $C_2, \cdots, C_N$. One can write down $C_i = C_1 \cdot M_{1,i}$, where $M_{1,i}$ is the rotation matrix from the 1st period to the $i$-th period.
  • Sum the total magnetic field $B_{total} = \sum_{i=1}^N B(C_i, P_1)$.

There is another way to do this. One can

  • Find the periodic points for $P_1$ on the plasma in reverse direction and mark them as $P_{-2}, \cdots, P_{-N}$. $P_{-i} = P_1 \cdot M_{1,-i}$.
  • Then we have $B(C_i, P_1) = B(C_1, P_{-i}) \cdot M_{1,i}$, where $M_{1,i} \cdot M_{1,-i} = I$. The total magnetic field is now $B_{total} = \sum_{i=1}^N B(C_1, P_{-i})\cdot M_{1,i}$. Here, $P_{-1}=P_{1}$

By doing so, we save the computation to map the entire coil. Instead, we only need to find the (reversely-)periodic points and rotate the calculated magnetic field. It should be faster, but rigorous evaluations on the reduction of operations need further justifications.

If the number of toroidal field periodicity is $N$, the toroidal periodicity means $R(\theta, \phi+i\frac{2\pi}{N}) = R(\theta, \phi)$ and $Z(\theta, \phi+i\frac{2\pi}{N}) = Z(\theta, \phi)$, where $i=0, 1, \cdots, N-1$. In Cartesian coordinates, the operation of rotating a point or vector by $\Delta \phi$ (count-clockwise) can be achieved by multiplying a permutation matrix, $$ M = \begin{pmatrix} \cos(\Delta \phi) & \sin(\Delta \phi)& 0 \\ -\sin(\Delta \phi)& \cos(\Delta \phi)& 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} $$

Stellarator symmetry¶

The stellarator symmetry means $R(-\theta, -\phi) = R(\theta, \phi)$ and $Z(-\theta, -\phi) = -Z(\theta, \phi)$. It has different meanings for scalars and vectors Dewar \& Hudson00216-9), \begin{align} S \{ f(r, \phi, z) \} & = f(r, -\phi, -z) , \\ S \{ \vec{F}(r, \phi, z) \} & = \vec{F}(-r, \phi, z) \ , \end{align} for arbitrary scalar function $f(r, \phi, z)$ and vector function $\vec{F}(r, \phi, z)$. Operator $S \{ \}$ means the stellarator symmetric operator. The operation on scalar functions in Cartesian coordinates can be interpreted as a rotation of $180^o$ over the $x$-axis, which has the following rotation matrix, $$ S_s = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix} $$ while the operation on vector functions is $$ S_v = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} $$

FOCUS achieves the stellarator symmetry by doing the following operations,

  • Find the symmetric point (of the evaluation point on the plasma) by $P_{S} = P \cdot S_s$.
  • Calculate $B(C1, P_S)$ and find the symmetric vector $B(C_S, P_1) = B(C1, P_S) \cdot S_v$.

Numerical details¶

Each coil will have a flag/property symm to indicate if the coil is periodic and/or stellarator symmetric. In bfield.f90, subroutine bfield0 calculates the magnetic field $(tBx, tBy, tBz)$ generated at $(x, y, z)$ from all the coils. It is realized by the following loops.

! check if the coil is stellarator symmetric
  select case (coil(icoil)%symm) 
  case ( 0 )
     cs  = 0
     Npc = 1
  case ( 1 )
     cs  = 0
     Npc = Nfp
  case ( 2) 
     cs  = 1
     Npc = Nfp
  end select
  ! periodicity and stellarator symmetry
  do ip = 1, Npc
     do is = 0, cs
        ! find the point on plasma by rotating in reverse direction. + symmetric
        xx = ( x*cosnfp(ip) + y*sinnfp(ip) )
        yy = (-x*sinnfp(ip) + y*cosnfp(ip) ) * (-1)**is
        zz =  z * (-1)**is
        Bx = zero; By = zero; Bz = zero
        ... ! Biot-Savart law
        ! sum all the contributions
        tBx = tBx + (Bx*cosnfp(ip) - By*sinnfp(ip))*(-1)**is
        tBy = tBy + (By*cosnfp(ip) + Bx*sinnfp(ip))
        tBz = tBz +  Bz
     enddo
  enddo

How to use¶

The periodicity (and stellarator symmetry) of the plasma boundary is controlled by IsSymmetric:

  • 0: No periodicity or stellarator symmetry, Nzeta for $\zeta \in [0,2\pi]$.
  • 1: Periodicity enforced, Nzeta for $\zeta \in [0,2\pi/N]$.
  • 2: Both periodicity and stellarator symmetry enforced, Nzeta for $\zeta \in [0,\pi/N]$.

The number of periodicity, $N$, is determined by the plasma boundary file. By using IsSymmetric = 1, 2, we can reduce the required number for toroidal discretizations.

The coil (and stellarator symmetry) is controlled by coil(icoil)%symm. It has the following options.

  • 0: No periodicity or stellarator symmetry.
  • 1: Periodicity enforced (also applied to self-symmetric coils).
  • 2: Both periodicity and stellarator symmetry enforced.

The coil(icoil)%symm is determined by

  • case_init = -1 or 1: coil(icoil)%symm = IsSymmetric
  • case_init = 0: coil(icoil)%symm is read from the focus file. There is an additional term in the file. Here is an example.

Verifications and benchmark¶

I am going to use the rotating ellipse for verifying and benchmarking the new implementation. There are three branches envolved, master, develop, and symmetry. The master branch is currently at v0.9.01 and the develop branch is ahead of the master with new implementation of separating the limiter surface for the funtion of coil-plasma separation ( check #17 and #42). The symmetry branch is ahead of the develop branch with the latest implementation.

I didn't turn on the toroidal flux as the Bnormal is normalized with |B|. For each case, I used 32 CPUs with 20 iterations of CG. Following is the base input file.

Some observations:

  • The stellarator symmetry (and periodicity) in FOCUS is working. All the coils are expectingly close (identical). Please check the final coils and Poincare plots below.
  • By enforcing stellarator symmetry (and periodicity) for the plasma boundary (IsSymmetric=1,2), we need lower resolution in the toroidal angle, which leads less computation time. (compare case 6 vs 7)
  • By enforcing stellarator symmetry (and periodicity) for the coils (coil(icoil)%symm=1,2), we have less variables, which also leads less computation time. (compare case 4 vs 7)
  • Bnormal function is not normalized by the surface area, that's why the values of full torus is double of the half case (Nfp=2) and four times of the quarter case (stellarator symmetry). length and cssep are normalized to the number of coils.
  • The discrepancy between case 1 and 2 is caused by the value of cssep_factor (default is $0$ in case 1, $4$ in case 2 and others).
